    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3385325648" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3385325648" />
    <a title="Peter" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17131437-peter"><img alt="Peter" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1596549109p2/17131437.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3385325648?book_show_action=true">Jun 10, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Peter" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Peter" href="/user/show/17131437-peter">Peter</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17131437-peter?shelf=fiction-thriller">fiction-thriller</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3385325648" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2725880992740299499"><i>Mount Dragon</i> (1996) by Douglas Preston and Lincoln Child is subtitled &quot;A Pandemic of Apocalyptic Proportions,&quot; we&apos;ve been here before with Preston and Child and their eerie mix of science and mystery. This is a variation on the mad scientist-corrupt corporation theme. This is one of their earlier contributions and demonstrates how much their writing has improved over the subsequent 25 years. <br/><br/>A patient with psychosis and delusions is admitted to Dr. Lloyd Fossey&apos;s Involuntary Unit at Featherwood </span>
  <span id="freeText2725880992740299499" style="display:none"><i>Mount Dragon</i> (1996) by Douglas Preston and Lincoln Child is subtitled "A Pandemic of Apocalyptic Proportions," we've been here before with Preston and Child and their eerie mix of science and mystery. This is a variation on the mad scientist-corrupt corporation theme. This is one of their earlier contributions and demonstrates how much their writing has improved over the subsequent 25 years. <br /><br />A patient with psychosis and delusions is admitted to Dr. Lloyd Fossey's Involuntary Unit at Featherwood Park psychiatric hospital in Albuquerque. (A nit: later his first name will be David.) Much to Fossey's surprise, the patient is himself a doctor—Dr. Franklin Burt, a well-known doctor whose lectures Fossey had attended when at Yale. Burt had been driving from the GeneDyne laboratory in Albuquerque with a bottle of Angel Dust (PCP). In a car accident the bottle broke, showering him with the PCP and creating extreme psychosis. The Albuquerque hospital had magnified this with doses of Haldol and sent the raving lunatic to Featherwood Park. Now Burt seems sane again, but not quite . . . when Fossey visits him Burt starts shouting "Poor Alpha," and begins thrashing and screaming. <br /><br />Dr. Guy Carson, a biogenetics technician, is late for work at GeneDyne's New Jersey headquarters. His boss reminds him again about lateness and shows him to a videoconference room where Carson has a one-on-one with GeneDyne's founder, Brentwood Scopes. "Boy," Carson thinks, "Lateness must be a high crime!" But the topic isn't lateness—Carson is being reassigned for six months to the company's Mount Dragon Remote Testing Research Facility at a remote site in New Mexico—Carson will be Burt's replacement at Mount Dragon. <br /><br />When Carson arrives at Mount Dragon he's met by the Assistant Director, John Singer, who assures him that this project has the very highest priority. Soon he's had a tour of the only Level-5 bio lab in the world and he's met his newly-arrived assistant, the irrascible and aloof Dr. Susana Cabeza de Vaca (Cabeza de Vaca = "Cowhead"). He's also met Jonathan Nye, Mount Dragon's security chief. Nye is a rather odd figure wearing a suit and a pith helmet. Nye's main eye is on the storied Mondragon gold treasure reported hidden in the area; his "hobby" is riding into the desert and exploring.<br /><br />The scene shifts to Harvard University where a geneticist named Charles Levine is lecturing his class on toxic pathogens. Guy Carson was Levine's former student: Levine remembers him as very smart, very argumentative, and very irritating. Levine is showing his class several satellite photos from 1985 of a Russian town where human bodies litter the streets but all other animals have been unaffected. <br /><br />That town had a biogenetics lab that had accidentally released a pathogen fatal only to people. The pathogen, called Strain 232, had a 100 percent fatality rate and was contagious well before the patient becomes ill; there is no warning! It still lurks in the area but there are no humans left to be attacked. Levine is an opponent of genetic engineering to improve the human race, and he concludes his lecture with <i>
  <blockquote>This is the future of bioengineering.</blockquote>
</i>Back at Mount Dragon there is a serious safety breach. A chimpanzee infected with an experimental pathogen called X-FLU escapes his cage and attacks several workers protected by bubble suits. Some suits are breached and one worker is scratched by the chimp. The result is catastrophic: her brain swelled until her skull literally explodes. An autopsy is performed, the body is cremated, and OSHA is informed. Soon a second event occurs—a biologist eating dinner blinds himself in one eye with his fork; the stimulus seems to be his hearing the phrase<i>
  <blockquote>If thine eye offend thee, pluck it out!</blockquote>
</i>He is placed under observation.<br /><br />An OSHA investigator named Gilbert Teece arrives. Teece is a former Brit whose interrogative style is a relentlessly cheerful voice masking a relentlessly inquisitive mind. Teece has done his homework on the backgrounds of every GeneDyne employee involved in X-FLU, and he <i>will</i> cheerfully tease out the truth. We hope that all OSHA investigators are like him; we suspect not! But Teece disappears in the middle of his investigation and Carson wonders whether Jonathan Nye had disappeared him.<br /><br />As the story unfolds, the team at Mount Dragon begins to show strange behavior: hallucinations, unintelligible outbursts, self-destructive acts, and so on. Carson investigates and traces it to a new about-to-be-launched product called <i>PurBlood</i>, an artificial blood. Testing was completed at Mount Dragon just before Carson he and Cowhead arrived at the site. Carson found out that to add credibility and confidence to its marketing program, all of the Mount Dragon team had been given a partial transplant of the product. Now they are all going off the rails as haywire genetic changes affect them. <br /><br />As Carson snoops around, assisted by Susana, Nye learns that Carson is snooping and targets him. Nye's close attention induces the two miscreants to flee by horse across the desert and the famous Malpaise lava fields, with Nye in close pursuit. Nye is especially pissed because before fleeing from the Mount Dragon Facility they had blown it up: everyone there except them had been infected, and if allowed to go free they could start a pandemic. But whatever the reason, Nye took the destruction personally.<br /><br />Carson and Cowhead are at a disadvantage: Nye has the better horse, more water, a Holland &amp; Holland .50 caliber double -barreled rifle, and he knows the area much better. They are on the edge of death when they come across an antelope recently killed by coyotes. Carson—a New Mexico native—knows that coyotes rarely roam far from water, so they track the coyotes back to a hidden water supply at the foot of the Fra Cristóbal mountains. They and their horses are saved. <br /><br />Meanwhile, Nye is beginning to hallucinate but he's still lucid enough to set up a perch on the lava flow from which he can scan a broad area where he expects to see Cason and Cowhead pass. His trusty H&amp;H is readied and has the supplies to wait two days for them to pass through. <br /><br />Will Nye get the dynamic duo? Will the Mondragon gold be discovered? Will the Apocalypse occur? Will Professor Levine stop the development of toxic viruses? There are many questions left to be answered.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="2725880992740299499" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

